Flight Delay Data Linear Model Machine Learning.

Interesting to see that a model using 19 variables that are a mix of numeric and dummy variables produced very good prediction models for both departure and arrival delay times. However, dropping some the of the sparsely populated variables such as Carrier_delay while adding dummy variables for weekdays completely ruined the model. R2 scores for the model dropped from >.95 to <.40.

# Least absolute shrinkage and selection operator
# Performs both variable selection and regularization in order to enhance the prediction accuracy and interpretability
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

lasso = Lasso(alpha=.01).fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_scaled)
predictions = lasso.predict(X_test_scaled)

MSE_l_dc = mean_squared_error(y_test_scaled, predictions)
r2_l_dc = lasso.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_scaled)
In [53]:
# Handles any potential multicollinearity that may exist amongst variables

from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

ridge = Ridge(alpha=.01).fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_scaled)
predictions = ridge.predict(X_test_scaled)

MSE_r_dc = mean_squared_error(y_test_scaled, predictions)
r2_r_dc = ridge.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_scaled)
In [54]:
# method that linearly combines the L1 and L2 penalties of the lasso and ridge methods.
# L1 -> Uses a cartesian (vector) coordinate system for error measurement instead of straight prediction - original values.
# L2 -> Uses euclidean distance (square root of sum of squares)

from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet

elasticnet = ElasticNet(alpha=.01).fit(X_train_scaled, y_train_scaled)
predictions = elasticnet.predict(X_test_scaled)

MSE_e_dc = mean_squared_error(y_test_scaled, predictions)
r2_e_dc = elasticnet.score(X_test_scaled, y_test_scaled)
